Thera Bank Personal Loan Campaign¶

Data Description:¶

The file Bank.xls contains data on 5000 customers. The data include customer demographic information (age, income, etc.), the customer's relationship with the bank (mortgage, securities account, etc.), and the customer response to the last personal loan campaign (Personal Loan). Among these 5000 customers, only 480 (= 9.6%) accepted the personal loan that was offered to them in the earlier campaign.

Domain:¶

Banking

Context:¶

This case is about a bank (Thera Bank) whose management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors). A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio with a minimal budget.

Attribute Information:¶

  • Customer ID
  • Age: Customer's age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Avg. spending on credit cards per month
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate; 3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any
  • Personal Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign?
  • Securities Account: Does the customer have a securities account with the bank?
  • CD Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank?
  • Online: Does the customer use internet banking facilities?
  • Credit card: Does the customer use a credit card issued by the bank?

Learning Outcomes:¶

  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Preparing the data to train a model
  • Training and making predictions using a classification model Modelevaluation

Objective:¶

The classification goal is to predict the likelihood of a liability customer buying personal loans.

Get Data Model Ready¶

Data Model -1¶

Steps for creating the optimzed data model¶
  1. Drop customer ID and Zip code columns as they don't add any significane in predicting the success ratio
  2. Replace the categorical values of Education
  3. Impute -ve values of Experience column with absolute values
  4. Get dummies for categorical columns which don't have (0,1) values
  5. Drop additional columns which will not add value to the model

  3. Impute -ve values of Experience column with absolute values
  4. Get dummies for categorical columns which don't have (0,1) values
  5. Dropping 801 rows which don't have any relationship with the bank

# plot the confusion matrix in terms of heatmap for better visualization. 

def draw_cm(actual,predicted):
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual,predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm,annot=True, linewidth=0.05, fmt='.2f', xticklabels=[0,1], yticklabels=[0,1])
    plt.ylabel('observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

6. Give Business understanding of your model? (5 marks)¶

6.1. Business understanding from exploratory data analysis (EDA)¶

  1. There is skewness of data for the relevant features that will be used for modeling. Most of it is positive skewnewss as we dropped ZIP code column.


  2. Age and Experience appear to be normally distributed tending to be negligibly -ve skewed. Income, CCAvg, Mortgage are visiblly +ve skewed.


  3. Visualization between Age and Personal loan provides a healthy distribution across the age groups.
    • Visualization between Family and Personal loan provides no trends in the data set.
    • Visualization between Experience and Personal loan provides no trends in data set.
    • Visualization between Income and Personal loan provides some trends. It says that as the income increases the application for personal loan also increases. But it isn't a consistent upward trend.
    • Visualization between Education and Personal loan indicates that more the education level, more is the application for personal loan.
    • Scatterplot between Age and Income indicates that across the age groups, higher the income higher is the application for personal loan
    • Scatterplot between Age and Mortgage indicates that across the age groups, higher the mortgage, more are the chances of applying for personal loan.

  4. The correlation plot doesn't indicate significant correlation between variables.
    • Age and Experience have an obvious hight correlation
    • Income and Personal loan have a strong +ve correlation
    • Income and CCAvg have a strong +ve correlation
    • Loan and CD accounts have some +ve correlation and so is the case with CCAvg and Loan

6.2. Business understanding from Data Model¶

  1. Customer ID and ZIP code don't add any significant value to the model. So dropping these two columns.

  2. Although via EDA there is relationship established between the columns, none of them indicate causation. So, a conclusive decision can't be made on dropping these columns. Hence have retained the rest of the columns.

  3. For Data Model-1, the resulting data model is a imbalanced data set with class-1 at 10% and class-0 at 90%. An attempt was made to improve the class-1% in the dataset by dropping 801 rows of customers which didn't have any relationship with the bank.

  4. For Data Model-2, the resulting data model is a imbalanced data set with class-1 at 11.5% and class-0 at 88.5%. As there is no significant difference, a decision was taken to retain all rows of the dataset.

  5. Finally a decision was made to only fit the logistic regression model on the Data Model-1

6.3. Business understanding of Logistic regression model¶

  1. From the first iteration of the model, the following observations were made.
    • True Positive (TP) = 93
    • True Negative (TN) = 1341
    • False Positive (FP) = 10
    • False Negative(FN) = 56

    • Recall = 62%
    • Precision = 90%
    • F1 Score = 0.73
    • AUC = 0.80

Our objective is to increase the recall or lower the False Negatives.


The premise behind this reasoning is that higher the False Negative numbers, the campaign is not considering attracting certain segment of people who could have been potentially accepted the personal loan offered to them.

The objective would be to attract/target as many people as possible who can be potential personal loan applicants.

The bank considers a 9% conversion rate as a healthy rate. Calculating the conversion rate from the True Positive number that the model predicted from a test sample of 1500, turns out to be 6.2%.</font>

This is 2.8% below the conversion rate the bank considers healthy.

  1. Performing Model tuning on the Logistic regression model, the following observations were made.

    • True Positive (TP) = 129
    • True Negative (TN) = 1240
    • False Positive (FP) = 111
    • False Negative(FN) = 20

    • Recall = 86%
    • Precision = 53%

After model tuning, the recall has increased by 24% while the precision has decreased by 37%. The overall Positive conversions for a sample size of 1500 from the test data set increases to 129 (factoring in reduction in FN predicted by the model)

Again calculating the conversion rate from the True Positive number that the model predicted from a test sample of 1500, turns out to be 8.6%.. This is very close to the conversion percentage the bank considers healthy</font>

  1. The False Positive has increased to 7.5% but if the campaign budget can accommodate the additional segments of people without overstretching, this is a fair tradeoff and this will result in people accepting personal loan close to the %age the bank considers healthy.
